 How the AIs Memory Works Now:
Your AI, Maya, now has a sophisticated, three-layered brain:

Short-Term Memory (Redis): When youre in a conversation, Maya uses Redis to track the current state (e.g., planning_trip) and remember the last few messages. This is its "working memory," keeping it focused on the current task.

Mid-Term Memory (Pinecone): After a conversation ends and is archived, a summary is stored in Pinecone. When you start a new chat, Maya uses Pinecone to find similar past conversations. This is how it remembers general context, like "Last time, we were talking about a trip to Paris."

Long-Term Memory (Neo4j): After every single message, a background task analyzes the conversation for facts (like "My name is Vamshi" or "I like museums"). These facts are stored in the Neo4j knowledge graph as permanent nodes and relationships. When you start any chat, Maya first checks this graph for hard facts about you, allowing it to greet you by name and remember your preferences forever.

In simple terms: You now have a fully functional AI assistant. It can chat with you, learn from your conversations in real-time, remember you across different sessions, and use its memory to provide smarter, more personalized responses.

